I forget who mentioned it, but someone had a great tip on the pit traps; if you're lev'd when you fall into one, you can just back up into a corner and you won't fall any farther.  Instead of slowly drifting down to the mobs at the bottom, this should buy you plenty of time to get everyone together and ready to head down to the bottom all at once.<br>
<br>
While I'm thinking of it, I thought I'd post a few thoughts on pulling in HS in hopes of avoiding more of those &quot;I got HT'd 4 times for 581 apiece&quot; deaths.<br>
<br>
1.  Each wing has a painting that hides a false wall right at the start of the wing, and there is a drop off behind it with no way back up.  Just jumping through the painting usually has meant anywhere from 3 to 6 mobs at once, which ain't much fun.  This part is a lot easier if the puller just sidles up so that they are just barely sticking through without falling; proximity aggro will take care of the pulls, and I don't think I ever got more than 2 that way at once.  It's much easier to get close to the edge if you come at it from an angle rather than straight on.<br>
<br>
2.  We had a couple of unnecessary deaths in the south wing (sorry Mugo and Codd) due to me trying to pull mobs through a little break in the wall.  We were pulling to the last room before the locked door that leads to the path to the east wing; I could make it through that hole no problem, but the mobs pathed the long way around, picking up friends on the way.  I noticed the pathing with the first pull, before the area had started repopping, but didn't think about it and so stupidly caused a big train that very nearly wiped us out.  When you get to that area, don't try to pull mobs through there.<br>
<br>
3.  There were a couple of rooms where mobs were tucked off to the side out of sight; if you got close enough to see them to target them for pacifying, they would aggro and bring their friends.  This made for a few unnecessarily large pulls (though Mugo once again handled the big pulls with aplomb).  I don't know if this would be too much of a PITA, but it did occur to me that it might be possible to have someone cast a bind sight spell on one of the mobs that could be seen in the room and then use F9 to target the other mobs for pacifying (cause pacify doesn't require a clear line of sight to the mob).  The person targeting would probably need a hotbutton saying something like &quot;Montag, please pacify %T now.&quot; so that they would know when a new mob was targeted.  With two hotbuttons you could even get a couple people pacifying, cutting out the slow recast time on pacify.  This sounds pretty complicated, but it might help us out some if we find ourselves without Mugo or Adoren for crowd control.  It wouldn't be a complete solution because I think you would still need a clear line of sight to actually hit the mob with a pulling spell or whatever, but it could cut down on some adds.<br>
<br>
Oh, and I'm thinking of changing my &quot;incoming&quot; message for HS to something like &quot;%T is incoming!  Casters stand up now or eat a harm touch!&quot;<br>
<br>
